article.description: Kimberly Dietz scored 20 points to lead unranked Kansas State to a 67-54 upset over Texas A&M (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) in the Big 12 opener for both teams Wednesday night.
article.headline: Dietz leads unranked Kansas State over Texas A&M
article.linkText: K-State serves No. 13 Texas A&M another upset
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) -- The Kansas State Wildcats remembered the sting of their last trip to College Station and were determined not to leave with that feeling again.

They erased the memory of that 27-point defeat two years ago with a 67-54 upset over Texas A&M (No. 12 ESPN/USA Today, No. 13 AP) on Wednesday night that ended the Aggies' 26-game home winning streak.

Kimberly Dietz scored 20 points to lead Kansas State to the win in the Big 12 opener for both teams.

"The last time we were here, we were taken to school so bad," Kansas State coach Deb Patterson said. "I remember it and I think a lot of these players do. Tonight, they were very determined to give a respectable effort."

Shalee Lehning, who had 10 rebounds and eight assists with four points, said the players didn't talk about the lopsided loss, but it was in the back of their minds.

"We were aware of how we played two years ago," she said. "It was definitely not competitive, not what the Big 12 requires. We knew we were going to have to play to the best of our ability to even play with them. We definitely got up for this game."

It is the second consecutive time the unranked Wildcats have upset a ranked A&M team. They beat then-No. 17 Texas A&M 48-45 in the last meeting a little more than a year ago.

That game was the last time the Wildcats had defeated a ranked team. Kansas State, which has won four straight overall, has won eight of the past nine meetings with Texas A&M (12-3, 0-1 Big 12).

Kansas State (9-5, 1-0) led by nine at halftime, but had a sluggish start to the second half with eight turnovers and no points in the first 4:58 and trailed by three points.

The Wildcats' first points of the half came on a jump shot by Lehning with 15:02 remaining that cut A&M's lead to 41-40.

"The game was won at the point guard position with Lehning," A&M coach Gary Blair said. "She didn't panic."

Kansas State regained the lead on a basket by Dietz with about 12 minutes left that made it 45-44 and the Wildcats wouldn't trail again. Kansas State outscored A&M 10-2 over the next 4 minutes to stretch its lead to 55-46.

"Defensively we did a real good job limiting their ability to get easy touches in the paint for any sustained period of time," Patterson said. "I thought our post defenders did a nice job of switching up how they defended."

The Aggies used strong defense and a full-court press to harass the Wildcats into mistakes and scored the first 12 points of the second half to take a 41-38 lead.

Blair was impressed with the composure of the Wildcats after A&M went ahead.

"They didn't rattle," he said. "They came right back and did what they had to."

Texas A&M was led by Takia Starks with 17 points and Danielle Gant added 14.

Starks brought the crowd to its feet when she stole the ball and was knocked to the court in the process, but continued to dribble while down. She got up while continuing her dribble and made her way down the court where she found Morenike Atunrase for the layup early in the second half.

Ashley Sweat added 14 points for Kansas State and Marlies Gipson had 11 points, nine rebounds and four blocks.

The Aggies led by two early in the first half before the Wildcats scored 12 straight points, fueled by five points by Gipson, to take a 17-7 lead 12 minutes before halftime.

Kansas State was ahead 27-15 before the Aggies went on a 14-2 run led by eight straight points by Starks to tie it at 29-all about 2 minutes before halftime.

Starks made one 3-pointer before sinking another just a few seconds later after a steal by Gant. Starks' jumper on the next possession, that was just short of the 3-point line, finished her scoring spurt.

Just seconds after the Aggies tied it up, Kansas State's Sweat made a 3-pointer to put the Wildcats back ahead. Kansas State scored the final six points of the half to lead 38-29 at halftime.

A subdued Blair sat at the press conference podium staring at the box score and shaking his head for several minutes after interviews were done.

"The game is about execution and hustle and we got beat on both counts," he said before his silent reflection.
